\par \lquote Harry! Good-oh!\rquote  said Bagman happily, looking around at him. \lquote Come in, come in, make yourself at home!\rquote 
\par Bagman looked somehow like a slightly overblown cartoon figure, standing amid all the pale-faced champions. He was wearing his old Wasp robes again.
\par \lquote Well, now we\rquote re all here \endash  time to fill you in!\rquote  said Bagman brightly. \lquote When the audience has assembled, I\rquote m going to be offering each of you this bag\rquote  \endash 
 he held up a small sack of purple silk, and shook it at them \endash  \lquote from which you will each select a small model of the thing you are about to face! There are different \endash  er \endash 
 varieties, you see. And I have to tell you something else too ... ah, yes ... your task is to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 collect the golden egg!\rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 
\par Harry glanced around. Cedric had nodded once, to show that he understood Bagman\rquote s words, and then started pacing around the tent again; he looked slightly green. Fleur Delacour and Krum hadn\rquote 
t reacted at all. Perhaps they thought they might be sick if they opened their mouths; that was certainly how Harry felt. But they, at least, had volunteered for this ...
\par And in no time at all, hundreds upon hundreds of pairs of feet could be heard passing the tent, their owners talking excit\-edly, laughing, joking ... Harry felt as separate from the crowd as if they were a different species. And then \endash 
 it felt about a second later to Harry \endash  Bagman was opening the neck of the purple silk sack.
\par \lquote Ladies first,\rquote  he said, offering it to Fleur Delacour.
\par She put a shaking hand inside the bag, and drew out a tiny, perfect model of a dragon \endash  a Welsh Green. It had the number \lquote two\rquote 
 around its neck. And Harry knew, by the fact that Fleur showed no sign of surprise, but rather a determined resigna\-tion, that he had been right: Madame Maxime had told her what was coming.
\par The same held true for Krum. He pulled out the scarlet Chinese Fireball. It had a number \lquote three\rquote  around its neck. He didn\rquote t even blink, just stared at the ground.
\par Cedric put his hand into the bag, and out came the blueish-grey Swedish Short-Snout, the number \lquote one\rquote  tied around its neck. Knowing what was left, Harry put his hand into the silk bag, and pulled out the Hungarian Horntail, and the number 
\lquote four\rquote . It stretched its wings as he looked down at it, and bared its minuscule fangs.
\par \lquote Well, there you are!\rquote  said Bagman. \lquote You have each pulled out the dragon you will face, and the numbers refer to the order in which you are to take on the dragons, do you see? Now, I\rquote 
m going to have to leave you in a moment, because I\rquote m commen\-tating. Mr Diggory, you\rquote re first, just go out into the enclosure when you hear a whistle, all right? Now ... Harry ... could I have a quick word? Outside?\rquote 
\par \lquote Er ... yes,\rquote  said Harry blankly, and he got up and went out of the tent with Bagman, who walked him a short way away, into the trees, and then turned to him with a fatherly expres\-sion on his face.
\par \lquote Feeling all right, Harry? Anything I can get you?\rquote 
\par \lquote What?\rquote  said Harry. \lquote I \endash  no, nothing.\rquote 
\par \lquote Got a plan?\rquote  said Bagman, lowering his voice conspiratorial\-ly. \lquote Because I don\rquote t mind sharing a few pointers, if you\rquote d like them, you know. I mean,\rquote  Bagman continued, lowering his voice still further, \lquote 
you\rquote re the underdog here, Harry ... any\-thing I can do to help ...\rquote 
\par \lquote No,\rquote  said Harry, so quickly he knew he had sounded rude, \lquote no \endash  I \endash  I\rquote ve decided what I\rquote m going to do, thanks.\rquote 
\par \lquote Nobody would }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 know, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 Harry,\rquote  said Bagman, winking at him.
\par \lquote No, I\rquote m fine,\rquote  said Harry, wondering why he kept telling people this, and wondering whether he had ever been less fine. \lquote I\rquote ve got a plan worked out, I \endash \rquote 
\par A whistle had blown somewhere.
\par \lquote Good Lord, I\rquote ve got to run!\rquote  said Bagman in alarm, and he hurried off.
\par Harry walked back to the tent, and saw Cedric emerging from it, greener than ever. Harry tried to wish him luck as he walked past, but all that came out of his mouth was a sort of hoarse grunt.
\par Harry went back inside to Fleur and Krum. Seconds later, they heard the roar of the crowd, which meant Cedric had entered the enclosure, and was now face to face with the living counterpart of his model ...
\par It was worse than Harry cou
ld ever have imagined, sitting there and listening. The crowd screamed ... yelled ... gasped like a single many-headed entity, as Cedric did whatever he was doing to get past the Swedish Short-Snout. Krum was still staring at the ground. Fleur had now tak
en to retracing Cedric\rquote s steps, round and round the tent. And Bagman\rquote s commentary made everything much, much worse ... horrible pictures formed in Harry\rquote s mind, as he heard: \lquote Oooh, narrow miss there, very narrow\rquote  ... 
\lquote He\rquote s taking risks, this one!\rquote  ... }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 \lquote Clever }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 move 
\endash  pity it didn\rquote t work!\rquote 
\par And then, after about fifteen minutes, Harry heard the deaf\-ening roar that could mean only one thing: Cedric had got past his dragon, and seized the golden egg.
\par \lquote Very good indeed!\rquote  Bagman was shouting. \lquote And now the marks from the judges!\rquote 
\par But he didn\rquote t shout out the marks; Harry supposed the judges were holding them up and showing them to the crowd.
\par \lquote One down, three to go!\rquote  Bagman yelled, as the whistle blew again. \lquote Miss Delacour, if you please!\rquote 
\par Fleur was trembling from head to foot; Harry felt more warmly towards her than he had done so far, as she left the tent with her head held high, and her hand clutching her wand. He and Krum were left alone, at opposite sides of the tent, avoiding each oth
er\rquote s gaze.
\par The same process started again ... \lquote Oh, I\rquote m not sure that was wise!\rquote  they could hear Bagman shouting gleefully. \lquote Oh ... nearly! Careful now ... good Lord, I thought she\rquote d had it then!\rquote 
\par Ten minutes later, Harry heard the crowd erupt into applause once more ... Fleur must have been successful, too. A pause, while Fleur\rquote s marks were being shown ... more clapping ... then, for the third time, the whistle.
\par \lquote And here comes Mr Krum!\rquote  cried Bagman, and Krum slouched out, leaving Harry quite alone.
\par He felt much more aware of his body than usual; very aware of the way his heart was pumping fast, and his fingers tingling with fear ... yet at the same time, he seemed to be outside him\-
self, seeing the walls of the tent, and hearing the crowd, as though from far away ...
\par \lquote Very daring!\rquote  Bagman was yelling, and Harry heard the Chinese Fireball emit a horrible, roaring shriek, while the crowd drew its collective breath. \lquote That\rquote s some nerve he\rquote s show\-ing \endash  and \endash  yes, he\rquote 
s got the egg!\rquote 
\par Applause shattered the wintery air like breaking glass; Krum had finished \endash  it would be Harry\rquote s turn at any moment.
\par He stood up, noticing dimly that his legs seemed to be made of marshmallow. He waited. And then he heard the whistle blow. He walked out through the entrance of the tent, 
the panic rising into a crescendo inside him. And now he was walking past the trees, through a gap in the enclosure fence.
\par He saw everything in front of him as though it was a very highly coloured dream. There were hundreds and hundreds of faces staring down at him from stands which had been mag\-icked there since he\rquote 
d last stood on this spot. And there was the Horntail, at the other end of the enclosure, crouched low over her clutch of eggs, her wings half furled, her evil, yellow eyes upon him, a monstrous
, scaly black lizard, thrashing her spiked tail, leaving yard-long gouge marks in the hard ground. The crowd was making a great deal of noise, but whether friendly or not, Harry didn\rquote 
t know or care. It was time to do what he had to do ... to focus his mind, entirely and absolutely, upon the thing that was his only chance ...
\par He raised his wand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 \lquote Accio Firebolt!\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 he shouted.
\par He waited, every fibre of him hoping, praying ... if it hadn\rquote t worked ... if it wasn\rquote t coming ... he seemed to be looking at everything
 around him through some sort of shimmering, transparent barrier, like a heat haze, which made the enclosure and the hundreds of faces around him swim strangely ...
\par And then he heard it, speeding through the air behind him; he turned and saw his Firebolt hurtling towards him around the edge of the woods, soaring into the enclosure, and stop\-
ping dead in mid-air beside him, waiting for him to mount. The crowd was making even more noise ... Bagman was shout\-ing something ... but Harry\rquote s ears were not working properly any more ... listening wasn\rquote t important ...
\par He swung his leg over the broom, and kicked off from the ground. And a second later, something miraculous happened ...
\par As he soared upwards, as the wind rushed through his hair, as the crowd\rquote s faces beca
me mere flesh-coloured pinpricks below, and the Horntail shrank to the size of a dog, he realised that he had left not only the ground behind, but also his fear ... he was back where he belonged ...
\par This was just another Quidditch match, that was all ... just another Quidditch match, and that Horntail was just another ugly opposing team ...
\par He looked down at the clutch of eggs, and spotted the gold one, gleaming against its cement-coloured fellows, residing safely between the dragon\rquote s front legs. \lquote OK,\rquote  Harry told himself, \lquote diversionary tactics ... let\rquote 
s go ...\rquote 
\par He dived. The Horntail\rquote s head followed him; he knew what it was going to do, and pulled out of the dive just in time; a jet of fire had been released exactly where he would have been had he not swerved away ... but Harry didn\rquote 
t care ... that was no more than dodging a Bludger ...
\par \lquote Great Scott, he can fly!\rquote  yelled Bagman, as the crowd shrieked and gasped. \lquote Are you watching this, Mr Krum?\rquote 
\par Harry soared higher in a circle; the Horntail was still follow\-ing his progress; its head revolving on its long neck \endash  if he kept this up, it would be nicely dizzy \endash  but better not push it too long, or it would be breathing fire again 
\endash 
\par Harry plummeted just as the Horntail opened its mouth, but this time he was less lucky \endash 
 he missed the flames, but the tail came whipping up to meet him instead, and as he swerved to the left, one of the long spikes grazed his shoulder, ripping his robes \endash 
\par He could feel it stinging, he could hear screaming and groans from the crowd, but the cut didn\rquote t seem to be deep ... now he zoomed around the back of the Horntail, and a possi\-bility occurred to him ...
\par The Horntail didn\rquote t seem to want to take off, she was too protective of her eggs. Though she writhed and twisted, furling and unfurling 
her wings and keeping those fearsome yellow eyes on Harry, she was afraid to move too far from them ... but he had to persuade her to do it, or he\rquote d never get near them ... the trick was to do it carefully, gradually ...
\par He began to fly, first this way, then the other, not near enough to make her breathe fire to stave him off, but still pos\-
ing a sufficient threat to ensure she kept her eyes on him. Her head swayed this way and that, watching him out of those vertical pupils, her fangs bared ...
\par He flew higher. The Horntail\rquote s head rose with him, her neck now stretched to its fullest extent, still swaying, like a snake before its charmer ...
\par Harry rose a few more feet, and she let out a roar of exasper\-ation. He was like a fly to her, a fly she was longing to
 swat; her tail thrashed again, but he was too high to reach now ... she shot fire into the air, which he dodged ... her jaws opened wide ...
\par \lquote Come on,\rquote  Harry hissed, swerving tantalisingly above her, \lquote come on, come and get me ... up you get, now ...\rquote 
\par And then she reared, spreading her great black leathery wings at last, as wide as those of a small aeroplane \endash 
 and Harry dived. Before the dragon knew what he had done, or where he had disappeared to, he was speeding towards the ground as fast as he could go, towards the eggs now unprotected by her clawed, front legs \endash 
 he had taken his hands off his Firebolt \endash  he had seized the golden egg \endash 
\par And with a huge spurt of speed, he was off, he was soaring out over the stands, the heavy egg safely under his uninjured arm, and it was as though somebody had just turned the volume back up \endash 
 for the first time, he became properly aware of the noise of the crowd, which was screaming and applaud\-ing as loudly as the Irish supporters at the World Cup \endash 
\par \lquote Look at that!\rquote  Bagman was yelling. \lquote Will you look at that! Our youngest champion is quickest to get his egg! Well, this is going to shorten the odds on Mr Potter!\rquote 
\par Harry saw the dragon-keepers rushing forwards to subdue the Horntail, and, over at the entrance to the enclosur
e, Professor McGonagall, Professor Moody and Hagrid hurrying to meet him, all of them waving him towards them, their smiles evident even from this distance. He flew back over the stands, the noise of the crowd pounding his eardrums, and came in smoothly t
o land, his heart lighter than it had been in weeks ... he had got through the first task, he had survived ...
\par \lquote That was excellent, Potter!\rquote  cried Professor McGonagall as he got off the Firebolt \endash  which from her was extravagant praise. He noticed that her hand shook as she pointed at his shoulder. \lquote You\rquote 
ll need to see Madam Pomfrey before the judges give out your score ... over there, she\rquote s had to mop up Diggory already ...\rquote 
\par \lquote Yeh did it, Harry!\rquote  said Hagrid hoarsely. \lquote Yeh did it! An\rquote  agains\rquote  the Horntail an\rquote  all, an\rquote  yeh know Charlie said that was the wors\rquote  \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Thanks, Hagrid,\rquote  said Harry loudly, so that Hagrid wouldn\rquote t blunder on and reveal that he had shown Harry the dragons beforehand.
\par Professor Moody looked very pleased, too; his magical eye was dancing in its socket.
\par \lquote Nice and easy does the trick, Potter,\rquote  he growled.
\par \lquote Right then, Potter, the first-aid tent, please ...\rquote  said Professor McGonagall.
\par Harry walked out of the enclosure, still panting, and saw Madam Pomfrey standing at the mouth of a second tent, look\-ing worried.
\par \lquote Dragons!\rquote  she said, in a disgusted tone, pulling Harry inside. The tent was divided into cubicles; he could make out Cedric\rquote s shadow through the canvas, but Cedric didn\rquote 
t seem to be badly injured; he was sitting up, at least. Madam Pomfrey examined Harry\rquote s shoulder, talking furiously all the while. \lquote Last year Dementors, this year dragons, what are they going to bring into this school next? You\rquote 
re very lucky ... this is quite shallow ... it\rquote ll need cleaning before I heal it up, though ...\rquote 
\par She cleaned the cut with a dab of some purple liquid which smoked and stung, but then poked his shoulder with her wand, and he felt it heal instantly.
\par \lquote Now, just sit quietly for a minute \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 sit! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 
And then you can go and get your score.\rquote 
\par She bustled out of the tent and he heard her go next door and say, \lquote How does it feel now, Diggory?\rquote 
\par Harry didn\rquote t want to sit still; he was still too full of adrena\-line. He got to his feet, wanting to see what was going on out\-side, but before he\rquote d reached the mouth of the tent, two people had come darting inside \endash 
 Hermione, followed closely by Ron.
\par \lquote Harry, you were brilliant!\rquote  Hermione said squeakily. There were fingernail marks on her face where she had been clutch\-ing it in fear. \lquote You were amazing! You really were!\rquote 
\par But Harry was looking at Ron, who was very white, and star\-ing at Harry as though he was a ghost.
\par \lquote Harry,\rquote  he said, very seriously, \lquote whoever put your name in that Goblet \endash  I \endash  I reckon they\rquote re trying to do you in!\rquote 
\par It was as though the last few weeks had never happened \endash  as though Harry was meeting Ron for the first time, right after he\rquote d been made champion.
\par \lquote Caught on, have you?\rquote  said Harry coldly. \lquote Took you long enough.\rquote 
\par Hermione stood nervously between them, looking from one to the other. Ron opened his mouth uncertainly. Harry knew Ron was about to apologise and, suddenly, he found he didn\rquote t need to hear it.
\par \lquote It\rquote s OK,\rquote  he said, before Ron could get the words out. \lquote Forget it.\rquote 
\par \lquote No,\rquote  said Ron, \lquote I shouldn\rquote t\rquote ve \endash \rquote 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 \lquote Forget it,\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 Harry said.
\par Ron grinned nervously at him, and Harry grinned back.
\par Hermione burst into tears.
\par \lquote There\rquote s nothing to cry about!\rquote  Harry told her, bewildered.
\par \lquote You two are so }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 stupid!\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 
she shouted, stamping her foot on the ground, tears splashing down her front. Then, before either of them could stop her, she had given both of them a hug, and dashed away, now positively howling.
\par \lquote Barking,\rquote  said Ron, shaking his head. \lquote Harry, c\rquote mon, they\rquote ll be putting up your scores ...\rquote 
\par Picking up the golden egg and his Firebolt, feeling more elated than he would have believed possible an hour ago, Harry ducked out of the tent, Ron by his side, talking fast.
\par \lquote You were the best, you know, no competition. C
edric did this weird thing where he Transfigured a rock on the ground ... turned it into a dog ... he was trying to make the dragon go for the dog instead of him. Well, it was a pretty cool bit of Transfiguration, and it sort of worked, because he did get
 the egg, but he got burnt as well \endash 
 the dragon changed its mind halfway through and decided it would rather have him than the labrador, he only just got away. And that Fleur girl tried this sort of charm, I think she was trying to put it into a trance \endash  we
ll, that kind of worked, too, it went all sleepy, but then it snored, and this great jet of flame shot out, and her skirt caught fire \endash  she put it out with a bit of water out of her wand. And Krum \endash  you won\rquote t believe this, but he didn
\rquote t even think of flying! He was probably the best after you, though. Hit it with some sort of spell right in the eye. Only thing is, it went tram\-pling around in agony and squashed half the real eggs \endash  they took marks off for that, he wasn
\rquote t supposed to do any damage to them.\rquote 
\par Ron drew breath as he and Harry reached the edge of the enclosure. Now that the Horntail had been taken away, Harry could see where the five judges were sitting \endash  right at the other end, in raised seats draped in gold.
\par \lquote It\rquote s marks out of ten from each one,\rquote  Ron said, and Harry, squinting up the field, saw the first judge \endash  Madame Maxime \endash  raise her wand in the air. What looked like a long, silver rib\-
bon shot out of it, which twisted itself into a large figure eight.
\par \lquote Not bad!\rquote  said Ron, as the crowd applauded. \lquote I suppose she took marks off for your shoulder ...\rquote 
\par Mr Crouch came next. He shot a number nine into the air.
\par \lquote Looking good!\rquote  Ron yelled, thumping Harry on the back.
\par Next, Dumbledore. He, too, put up a nine. The crowd were cheering harder than ever.
\par Ludo Bagman \endash  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 ten.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 
\par \lquote Ten?\rquote  said Harry in disbelief. \lquote But ... I got hurt ... what\rquote s he playing at?\rquote 
\par \lquote Harry, don\rquote t complain!\rquote  Ron yelled excitedly.
\par And now Karkaroff raised his wand. He paused for a moment, and then a number shot out of his wand, too \endash  four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 \lquote What?\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 Ron bellowed furiously. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 \lquote Four? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 You lousy biased scumbag, you gave Krum ten!\rquote 
\par But Harry didn\rquote t care, he wouldn\rquote t have cared if Karkaroff had given him zero; Ron\rquote s indignation on his behalf was worth about a hundred points to him. He didn\rquote t tell Ron t
his, of course, but his heart felt lighter than air as he turned to leave the enclosure. And it wasn\rquote t just Ron ... those weren\rquote 
t only Gryffindors cheering in the crowd. When it had come to it, when they had seen what he was facing, most of the school had been on his side, as well as Cedric\rquote s ... he didn\rquote 
t care about the Slytherins, he could stand whatever they threw at him now.
\par \lquote You\rquote re tied in first place, Harry! You and Krum!\rquote  said Charlie Weasley, hurrying to meet them as they set off back towards the school. \lquote Listen, I\rquote ve got to run, I\rquote ve got to go and send Mum an owl, I swore I
\rquote d tell her what happened \endash  but that was unbelievable! Oh yeah \endash  and they told me to tell you you\rquote ve got to hang around for a few more minutes ... Bagman wants a word, back in the champions\rquote  tent.\rquote 
\par Ron said he would wait, so Harry re-entered the tent, which somehow looked quite different now; friendly and welcoming. He thought back to how he\rquote d felt while dodging the Horntail, and compared it to the long wait before he\rquote d walked out 
to face it ... there was no comparison, the wait had been immeasur\-ably worse.
\par Fleur, Cedric and Krum all came in together.
\par One side of Cedric\rquote s face was covered in a thick orange paste, which was presumably mending his burn. He grinned at Harry when he saw him. \lquote Good one, Harry.\rquote 
\par \lquote And you,\rquote  said Harry, grinning back.
\par \lquote Well done, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 all}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133  of you!\rquote 
 said Ludo Bagman, bouncing into the tent, and looking as pleased as though he personally had just got past a dragon. \lquote Now, just a quick few words. You\rquote ve got a nice lo
ng break before the second task, which will take place at half past nine on the morning of February the twenty-fourth \endash  but we\rquote re giving you something to think about in the mean\-time! If you look down at those golden eggs you\rquote 
re all holding, you will see that they open ... see the hinges there? You need to solve the clue inside the egg \endash  because it will tell you what the second task is, and enable you to prepare for it! All clear? Sure? Well, off you go, then!\rquote 

\par Harry left the tent, rejoined Ron, and they st
arted to walk back around the edge of the Forest, talking hard; Harry wanted to hear what the other champions had done in more detail. Then, as they rounded the clump of trees behind which Harry had first heard the dragons roar, a witch leapt out from beh
ind them.
\par It was Rita Skeeter. She was wearing acid-green robes today; the Quick-Quotes Quill in her hand blended perfectly against them.
\par \lquote Congratulations, Harry!\rquote  she said, beaming at him. \lquote I won\-der if you could give me a quick word? How you felt facing that dragon? How you feel }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 
