\par But the boy was trying to fight the Dementors off, even though Harry could see their cold, draining power starting to affect him. The crowd were jeering, some of them on their feet, as the woman swept out of the dungeon, and the boy continued to struggle.

\par \lquote I\rquote m your son!\rquote  he screamed up at Crouch. \lquote I\rquote m your son!\rquote 
\par \lquote You are no son of mine!\rquote  bellowed Mr Crouch, his eyes bulging suddenly. \lquote I have no son!\rquote 
\par The wispy witch beside him gave a great gasp, and slumped in her seat. She had fainted. Crouch appeared not to have noticed.
\par \lquote Take them away!\rquote  Crouch roared at the Dementors, spit fly\-ing from his mouth. \lquote Take them away, and may they rot there!\rquote 
\par \lquote Father! Father, I wasn\rquote t involved! No! No! Father, please!\rquote 
\par \lquote I think, Harry, it is time to return to my office,\rquote  said a quiet voice in Harry\rquote s ear.
\par Harry started. He looked around. Then he looked on his other side.
\par There was an Albus Dumbledore sitting on his right, watching Crouch\rquote s son being dragged away by the Dementors \endash  and there was an Albus Dumbledore on his left, looking right at him.
\par \lquote Come,\rquote  said the Dumbledore on his left, and he put his hand under Harry\rquote s elbow. Harry felt himself rising into the air; the dungeon dissolved around him; for a
 moment, all was blackness, and then he felt as though he had done a slow-motion somersault, suddenly landing flat on his feet, in what seemed like the dazzling light of Dumbledore\rquote 
s sunlit office. The stone basin was shimmering in the cabinet in front of him, and Albus Dumbledore was standing beside him.
\par \lquote Professor,\rquote  Harry gasped, \lquote I know I shouldn\rquote t\rquote ve \endash  I didn\rquote t mean \endash  the cabinet door was sort of open and \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote I quite understand,\rquote  said Dumbledore. He lifted the basin, carried it over to his desk, placed it upon the polished top, and sat down in the chair behind it. He motioned Harry to sit down opposite him.
\par Harry did so, staring at the stone basin. The contents had returned to their original, silvery white state, swirling and rip\-pling beneath his gaze.
\par \lquote What is it?\rquote  Harry asked shakily.
\par \lquote This? It is called a Pensieve,\rquote  said Dumbledore. \lquote I sometimes find, and I am sure you know the feeling, that I simply have too many thoughts and memories crammed into my mind.\rquote 
\par \lquote Er,\rquote  said Harry, who couldn\rquote t truthfully say that he had ever felt anything of the sort.
\par \lquote At these times,\rquote  said Dumbledore, indicating the stone basin, \lquote I use the Pensieve. One simply siphons the excess thoughts from one\rquote s mind, pours them into the basin, and examines them at one\rquote s leisure. It bec
omes easier to spot pat\-terns and links, you understand, when they are in this form.\rquote 
\par \lquote You mean ... that stuff\rquote s your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \ai\af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 thoughts?\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af39 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\lang2057\langfe3081\langnp2057\insrsid15346133 
Harry said, staring at the swirling white substance in the basin.
\par \lquote Certainly,\rquote  said Dumbledore. \lquote Let me show you.\rquote 
\par Dumbledore drew his wand out of the inside of his robes, and placed the tip into his own silvery hair, near his temple. When he took the wand away, hair seemed to be clinging to it \endash 
