\par Dumbledore merely looked at him.
\par \lquote Er \endash  that\rquote s all,\rquote  said Harry.
\par \lquote I see,\rquote  said Dumbledore quietly. \lquote I see. Now, has your scar hurt at any other time this year, excepting the time it woke you up over the summer?\rquote 
\par \lquote No, I \endash  how did you know it woke me up over the sum\-mer?\rquote  said Harry, astonished.
\par \lquote You are not Sirius\rquote  only correspondent,\rquote  said Dumbledore. \lquote I have also been in contact with him ever since he left Hogwarts last year. It was I who suggested the mountainside cave as the safest place for him to stay.\rquote 

\par Dumbledore got up, and began walking up and down behind his desk. Every now and then, he placed his wand tip to his temple, removed another shining silver thought, and added it to the Pensieve. The thoughts inside began to swirl so fast that Harry couldn
\rquote t make out anything clearly; it was mere\-ly a blur of colour.
\par \lquote Professor?\rquote  he said quietly, after a couple of minutes.
\par Dumbledore stopped pacing, and looked at Harry.
\par \lquote My apologies,\rquote  he said quietly. He sat back down at his desk.
\par \lquote D\rquote you \endash  d\rquote you know why my scar\rquote s hurting me?\rquote 
\par Dumbledore looked very intently at Harry for a moment, and then said, \lquote I have a theory, no more than that ... It is my belief that your scar hurts both when Lord Voldemort is near you, and when he is feeling a particularly strong surge of hatred.
\rquote 
\par \lquote But ... why?\rquote 
\par \lquote Because you and he are connected by the curse that failed,\rquote  said Dumbledore. \lquote That is no ordinary scar.\rquote 
\par \lquote So you think ... that dream ... did it really happen?\rquote 
\par \lquote It is possible,\rquote  said Dumbledore. \lquote I would say \endash  probable. Harry \endash  did you see Voldemort?\rquote 
\par \lquote No,\rquote  said Harry. \lquote Just the back of his chair. But \endash  there wouldn\rquote t have been anything to see, would there? I mean, he hasn\rquote t got a body, has he? But ... but then how could he have held the wand?\rquote 
 Harry said slowly.
\par \lquote How indeed?\rquote  muttered Dumbledore. \lquote How indeed ...\rquote 
\par Neither Dumbledore nor Harry spoke for a while. Dumbledore was gazing across the room, every now and then placing his wand tip to his temple, and adding another shin\-ing, silver thought to the seething mass within the Pensieve.
\par \lquote Professor,\rquote  Harry said at last, \lquote do you think he\rquote s getting stronger?\rquote 
\par \lquote Voldemort?\rquote  said Dumbledore, looking at Harry over the Pensieve. It was the characteristic, piercing look Dumbledore had given him on other occasions, and always made Harry feel as though Dumbled
ore was seeing right through him, in a way that even Moody\rquote s magical eye could not. \lquote Once again, Harry, I can only give you my suspicions.\rquote 
\par Dumbledore sighed again, and he looked older, and wearier, than ever.
\par \lquote The years of Voldemort\rquote s ascent to power,\rquote  he said, \lquote 
were marked with disappearances. Bertha Jorkins has vanished without trace in the place where Voldemort was certainly known to be last. Mr Crouch, too, has disappeared ... within these very grounds. And there was a third disappearance, one which th
e Ministry, I regret to say, does not consider of any importance, for it concerns a Muggle. His name was Frank Bryce, he lived in the village where Voldemort\rquote 
s father grew up, and he has not been seen since last August. You see, I read the Muggle newspapers, unlike most of my Ministry friends.\rquote 
\par Dumbledore looked very seriously at Harry. \lquote These disap\-pearances seem to me to be linked. The Ministry disagrees \endash  as you may have heard, while waiting outside my office.\rquote 
\par Harry nodded. Silence fell between them again, Dumbledore extracting thoughts every now and then. Harry felt as though he ought to go, but his curiosity held him in his chair.
\par \lquote Professor?\rquote  he said again.
\par \lquote Yes, Harry?\rquote  said Dumbledore.
\par \lquote Er ... could I ask you about ... that court thing I was in ... in the Pensieve?\rquote 
\par \lquote You could,\rquote  said Dumbledore heavily. \lquote I attended it many times, but some trials come back to me more clearly than others ... particularly now ...\rquote 
\par \lquote You know \endash  you know the trial you found me in? The one with Crouch\rquote s son? Well ... were they talking about Neville\rquote s parents?\rquote 
\par Dumbledore gave Harry a very sharp look.
\par \lquote Has Neville never told you why he has been brought up by his grandmother?\rquote  he said.
\par Harry shook his head, wondering, as he did so, how he could have failed to ask Neville this, in almost four years of knowing him.
\par \lquote Yes, they were talking about Neville\rquote s parents,\rquote  said Dumbledore. \lquote His father, Frank, was an Auror just like Professor Moody. He and his wife were tortured for informa\-tion about Voldemort\rquote s whereabouts after he lost 
his powers, as you heard.\rquote 
\par \lquote So they\rquote re dead?\rquote  said Harry quietly.
\par \lquote No,\rquote  said Dumbledore, his voice full of a bitterness Harry had never heard there before, \lquote they are insane. They are both in St Mungo\rquote s Hospital for Magical Maladies and Injuries. I believe 
Neville visits them, with his grandmother, during the holidays. They do not recognise him.\rquote 
\par Harry sat there, horror-struck. He had never known ... never, in four years, bothered to find out ...
\par \lquote The Longbottoms were very popular,\rquote  said Dumbledore.
\par The attacks on them came after Voldemort\rquote 
s fall from power, just when everyone thought they were safe. Those attacks caused a wave of fury such as I have never known. The Ministry was under great pressure to catch those who had done it. Unfortunately, the Longbottoms\rquote  evidence was 
\endash  given their condition \endash  none too reliable.\rquote 
\par \lquote Then Mr Crouch\rquote s son might not have been involved?\rquote  said Harry slowly.
\par Dumbledore shook his head. \lquote As to that, I have no idea.\rquote 
\par Harry sat in silence once more, watching the contents of the Pensieve swirl. There were two more questions he was burning to ask ... but they concerned the guilt of living people ...
\par \lquote Er,\rquote  he said, \lquote Mr Bagman ...\rquote 
\par \lquote ... has never been accused of any Dark activity since,\rquote  said Dumbledore calmly.
\par \lquote Right,\rquote  said Harry hastily, staring at the contents of the Pensieve again, which were swirling more slowly now that Dumbledore had stopped adding thoughts. \lquote And ... er ...\rquote 
\par But the Pensieve seemed to be asking his question for him. Snape\rquote s face was swimming on the surface again. Dumbledore glanced down into it, and then up at Harry.
\par \lquote No more has Professor Snape,\rquote  he said.
\par Harry looked into Dumbledore\rquote s light-blue eyes, and the thing he really wanted to know spilled out of his mouth before he could stop it. \lquote What made you think he\rquote d really stopped supporting Voldemort, Professor?\rquote 
\par Dumbledore held Harry\rquote s gaze for a few seconds, and then said, \lquote That, Harry, is a matter between Professor Snape and myself.\rquote 
\par Harry knew that the interview was over; Dumbledore did not look angry, yet there was a finality in his tone that told Harry it was time to go. He stood up, and so did Dumbledore.
\par \lquote Harry,\rquote  he said, as Harry reached the door. \lquote Please do not speak about Neville\rquote s parents to anybody else. He has the right to let people know, when he is ready.\rquote 
\par \lquote Yes, Professor,\rquote  said Harry, turning to go.
\par \lquote And \endash \rquote 
\par Harry looked back.
\par Dumbledore was standing over the Pensieve, his face lit from beneath by its silvery spots of light, looking older than ever. He stared at Harry for a moment, and then said, \lquote Good luck with the third task.\rquote 
