s fondness for Muggles that has held him back at the Ministry all these years. Fudge thinks he lacks proper wizard\-ing pride.\rquote 
\par \lquote Then I need to send a message to him,\rquote  said Dumbledore. All those that we can persuade of the truth must be notified immediately, and Arthur is well placed to contact those at the Ministry who are not as short-sighted as Cornelius.\rquote 

\par \lquote I\rquote ll go to Dad,\rquote  said Bill, standing up. \lquote I\rquote ll go now.\rquote 
\par \lquote Excellent,\rquote  said Dumbledore. \lquote Tell him what has happened. Tell him I will be in direct contact with him shortly. He will need to be discreet, however. If Fudge thinks I am interfering at the Ministry \endash \rquote 
\par \lquote Leave it to me,\rquote  said Bill.
\par He clapped a hand on Harry\rquote s shoulder, kissed his mother on the cheek, pulled on his cloak, and strode quickly from the room.
\par \lquote Minerva,\rquote  said Dumbledore, turning to Professor McGonagall, \lquote I want to see Hagrid in my office as soon as possible. Also \endash  if she will consent to come \endash  Madame Maxime.\rquote 
\par Professor McGonagall nodded, and left without a word.
\par \lquote Poppy,\rquote  Dumbledore said to Madam Pomfrey, \lquote would you be very kind, and go down to Professor Moody\rquote 
s office, where I think you will find a house-elf called Winky in considerable distress? Do what you can for her, and take her back to the kitchens. I think Dobby will look after her for us.\rquote 
\par \lquote Very \endash  very well,\rquote  said Madam Pomfrey, looking startled, and she too left.
\par Dumbledore made sure that the door was closed, and that Madam Pomfrey\rquote s footsteps had died away, before he spoke again.
\par \lquote And now,\rquote  he said, \lquote it is time for two of our number to recognise each other for what they are. Sirius ... if you could resume your usual form.\rquote 
